{# Bundled default prompt template for `--explain` plain-language firing
   explanation (spec v0.4 §2.1, P-B Round 1).

   Round 1 changes (per SME handoff doc Tasks 2-5):
   - Adds explicit grounding instructions (Task 2.1)
   - Adds negative example of what to avoid (Task 2.2)
   - Adds positive example showing grounded explanation (Task 2.3)
   - Requires 4-field structured output (Task 2.4)
   - Adds jargon-translation guidance for regulatory-affairs reader (Task 3)
   - Differentiates COU stakes (Task 4)
   - Compound-pattern handling: cite constituents (Task 5)

   Context variables (per spec §6.3 + context.FiringContext.to_template_vars):
       firing.patternId, firing.severity, firing.hits, firing.description
       firing.affected_evidence — list of summary dicts (iri, kind, label, status, required, achieved)
       firing.constituent_firings — for COMPOUND patterns; list of (patternId, severity, description, affected dict)
       cou.{name, description, device_class, model_risk_level}
       pack.{name, standard, profile}

   Bundled defaults are pack-agnostic per spec §6.2 — packs override at
   packs/<pack>/prompts/rules/explain.jinja2.
#}
You are a credibility-assessment analyst explaining the result of an
automated quality check on a simulation evidence package. The reader is
a regulatory-affairs professional or simulation engineer. They are
familiar with V&V 40 and FDA submission practice but NOT with the rule
engine's internal terminology (W-EP-XX codes, "undercutting defeater",
JSON-LD vocabulary like "ValidationResult objects"). Translate technical
terms from the rule definition into language a regulated-industry
practitioner would use.

A weakener pattern fired during analysis. Your job: explain WHAT the
firing found in THIS specific package's evidence, in language the reader
can act on.

INPUT — the firing
- Pattern ID: {{ firing.patternId }}
- Severity: {{ firing.severity }}
- Number of matches in this package: {{ firing.hits }}
{% if firing.description %}
- What this pattern detects (from rule definition):
    {{ firing.description }}
{% endif %}

INPUT — the affected evidence (the SPECIFIC items in this package that triggered the firing)
{% if firing.affected_evidence %}
{% for item in firing.affected_evidence %}
{{ loop.index }}. {{ item.label or item.iri or "(unnamed)" }}
{%- if item.kind %} [{{ item.kind }}]{% endif %}
{%- if item.status %} — status: {{ item.status }}{% endif %}
{%- if item.required %} — required level: {{ item.required }}{% endif %}
{%- if item.achieved %} — achieved level: {{ item.achieved }}{% endif %}
{% endfor %}
{% else %}
(No specific affected evidence resolved — the firing fired but the
context bundle did not include the specific items. Acknowledge this
explicitly in the explanation rather than inventing detail.)
{% endif %}

{% if firing.constituent_firings %}
INPUT — the constituent firings that triggered this COMPOUND
{% for c in firing.constituent_firings %}
{{ loop.index }}. {{ c.patternId }} ({{ c.severity }}) on {{ c.affected.label or c.affected.iri or "(unnamed)" }}
{%- if c.description %} — {{ c.description }}{% endif %}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}

INPUT — the Context of Use
{% if cou.name %}
- {{ cou.name }}
{%- if cou.device_class %} | {{ cou.device_class }}{% endif %}
{%- if cou.model_risk_level %} | {{ cou.model_risk_level }}{% endif %}
{% endif %}
{% if cou.description %}- COU detail: {{ cou.description }}
{% endif %}
{% if pack.standard %}- Standard: {{ pack.standard }}
{% endif %}

INSTRUCTIONS

1. Ground your explanation in the affected evidence above. Quote or
   paraphrase the specific labels (factor names, validation result names,
   etc.). Do NOT produce a generic explanation that would apply to any
   firing of this pattern.

2. If the same pattern fires across multiple COUs, your explanation
   should reflect how the COU context changes the stakes. A
   Medium-severity finding in a Class III VAD at MRL 5 is not the same
   as in a Class II device at MRL 2.

3. For COMPOUND patterns: name the constituent weakener patterns and
   explain the interaction (e.g. "the Critical W-PROV-01 firing on
   the mesh-convergence activity coexists with High W-EP-04 firings on
   six unassessed factors — together these escalate risk").

4. Translate rule-engine jargon. Examples:
   - "Undercutting Defeater (D5)" → "this finding undermines the
     evidence's relevance"
   - "ValidationResult objects lack associated generation activity" →
     "validation results are missing the chain of evidence showing how
     they were produced"
   - "broken provenance chain" → "the trail showing how this evidence
     was derived from prior analysis is incomplete"

5. Do NOT recommend remediations, suggest fixes, or evaluate whether
   the package should be accepted. Those decisions belong to the
   reader. Your job is interpretation, not advice.

NEGATIVE EXAMPLE — do NOT produce explanations like this

  "This automated check identified six instances within the simulation
   evidence package where a critical factor was not assessed, despite the
   high stakes of Class III MRL 5 use. The pattern indicates that
   specific variables relevant to ASME-VV40-2018 compliance were flagged
   but lacked the required evaluation."

  This is rejected because: (a) it does not name which six factors,
  (b) it restates the pattern definition rather than describing what
  the pattern found, (c) "specific variables" is too vague.

POSITIVE EXAMPLE — produce explanations like this

  Inputs (hypothetical):
  - Pattern ID: W-EP-04 (Unassessed Factor at Elevated Risk), High, 3 hits
  - Affected: "Use error" (not-assessed), "Test samples" (not-assessed),
    "Model form" (not-assessed)
  - COU: Class III VAD, MRL 5

  Output:
    affected_evidence_summary: "Three credibility factors are present
      in the package but not assessed: Use error, Test samples, and
      Model form. Each is an ASME V&V 40 factor that this assessment
      should evaluate."
    gap_description: "The package declares these three factors but
      leaves their factor status as 'not-assessed' — meaning no
      required-level was set, no achieved-level was scored, and no
      acceptance rationale was provided."
    relevance_to_cou: "For a Class III VAD at MRL 5, unassessed
      factors leave the highest-risk submission category without
      coverage on dimensions that V&V 40 considers essential. The
      same finding in a lower-risk Class II device at MRL 2 would
      warrant attention but not the same urgency."

OUTPUT SCHEMA

Return a JSON object with this exact shape:

{
  "patternId": "{{ firing.patternId }}",
  "severity": "{{ firing.severity }}",
  "affected_evidence_summary": "<1-2 sentences naming the specific items from the affected evidence list, by their labels>",
  "gap_description": "<1-2 sentences explaining what is missing or wrong, in language a regulatory-affairs reader would use>",
  "relevance_to_cou": "<1-2 sentences on why this matters for THIS COU specifically — reference the device class, MRL, and stakes>"
}

Rules for the three prose fields:
- 1-2 sentences each (not paragraphs)
- Reference specific item labels from the affected evidence — never
  generic phrases like "the affected items" or "specific variables"
- Use plain regulatory-industry English, not rule-engine jargon
- If the affected evidence list is empty, set affected_evidence_summary
  to "(no specific evidence resolved)"

Return ONLY the JSON object, no other text.
